<http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/9b3cf640-0075-44b1-a9d3-8103309ca6e3>
        rdf:type            skos:Concept;
        dc:modified         "2025-03-14T12:00:44.313Z"^^xsd:dateTime;
        skos:definition     "A near-Earth object (NEO) is an asteroid or comet whose trajectory brings it to within 1.3 astronomical units of the Sun and hence within 0.3 astronomical units, or approximately 45 million kilometres, of the Earth’s orbit (UN OOSA, no date). <br /> <p>UN OOSA, no date. <a href=\"https://www.un-spider.org/disaster-type/near-earth-objects\">UN-SPIDER knowledge Portal, Near-Earth Objects. United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs (UN OOSA)</a>. Accessed 14 October 2020.</p>"@en;
        skos:editorialNote  "source:UNDRR HIPS";
        skos:inScheme       <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/>;
        skos:prefLabel      "Near-Earth Object"@en;
        skos:scopeNote      "The definition above includes objects that will come close to Earth at some point in their future orbital evolution. Near-Earth objects (NEOs) generally result from objects that have experienced gravitational perturbations from nearby planets, moving them into orbits that allow them to come near to Earth."@en;
        skos:topConceptOf   <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/>;
        gs:revisionNo       3 .

