<http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/a96c80e6-7ed5-4277-8a0a-366456d8b510>
        rdf:type           skos:Concept;
        dc:created         "2025-06-06T12:54:25.708Z"^^xsd:dateTime;
        dc:modified        "2025-06-06T12:57:57.927Z"^^xsd:dateTime;
        skos:definition    "Positionality refers to where one is located in relation to their various social identities (gender, race, class, ethnicity, ability, geographical location etc.); the combination of these identities and their intersections shape how we understand and engage with the world, including our knowledges, perspectives, and teaching practices (Queen's University, n.d)."@en;
        skos:historyNote   "Wilson, C., Janes, G., & Williams, J. (2022). Identity, positionality and reflexivity: relevance and application to research paramedics. British paramedic journal, 7(2), 43–49. https://doi.org/10.29045/14784726.2022.09.7.2.43\n\nQueen’s University Centre for Teaching and Learning. (n.d.). Positionality statement. https://www.queensu.ca/ctl/resources/equity-diversity-inclusivity/positionality-statement"@en;
        skos:inScheme      <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/>;
        skos:prefLabel     "Positionality"@en;
        skos:scopeNote     "Often used to refer specifically to researchers and the position a researcher has chosen to adopt within a given research study. It necessitates the researcher consciously examining their own identity to allow the reader to assess the effect of their personal characteristics and perspectives in relation to the study population, the topic under study and the research process (Wilson et al., 2022)."@en;
        skos:topConceptOf  <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/>;
        gs:revisionNo      6 .

