<http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/ce734015-d0e1-4aef-8cce-457ad3338ea0>
        rdf:type            skos:Concept;
        dc:modified         "2025-03-14T12:00:44.313Z"^^xsd:dateTime;
        skos:definition     "Wind is air motion relative to the Earth’s surface. Unless otherwise specified, only the horizontal component is considered (WMO, 1992). <br /> <p>WMO, 1992. <a href=\"https://library.wmo.int/doc_num.php?explnum_id=4712\">International Meteorological Vocabulary. WMO-No. 182. World Meteorological Organization (WMO)</a>. Accessed 25 November 2019.</p>"@en;
        skos:editorialNote  "source:UNDRR HIPS";
        skos:inScheme       <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/>;
        skos:prefLabel      "Wind"@en;
        skos:scopeNote      "Wind velocity is an important consideration in relation to, for example, airborne pollution and the landing of aircraft (WMO, 2018). Surface wind is considered mainly as a two-dimensional vector quantity specified by two numbers representing direction and speed (WMO, 2018). The extent to which wind is characterised by rapid fluctuations is referred to as gustiness, and single fluctuations are called gusts (WMO, 2018)."@en;
        skos:topConceptOf   <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/>;
        gs:revisionNo       3 .

